HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Sunday, 09-Feb-97 20:31:37 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 27-Sep-96 19:06:30 GMT
Content-length: 5973
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Keating's Corner</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff">
<center><h2>
Keating's Corner</h2>
<P><br><b>
The Case for Competition in Education
<p></b>
by Matthew Carolan and Raymond J. Keating
<P>
<i>April 8, 1996</i>
<p><br>
<hr width="85%">
<p><br>
</center>
<blockquote>
     In a recent Washington Post article, Nobel-Prize-winning economist Milton Friedman warned of a growing danger in American society. We are, he said, splitting into two types of people: those who are well-educated and highly skilled -- the"cognitive elite" -- and those who are being left behind by our current educational system -- low-skilled, poorly educated, and unable to compete technologically and politically in a rapidly changing world.    
<P>
 The legendary Gordon Moore of Intel, who famously predicted the rapid technological change brought on the by the microchip, expresses similar concerns.     These men, and others, are not worried about technical or vocational skills per se. They are concerned about the way our society is changing from an industrial to an information-based society.  A society making more demands on the minds, and less on the muscles of future American workers. These workers will need like never before the power to read, write, think critically, and master advanced concepts.     
<P>
Our school system, however, has shown that it is not up to the task.  In New York, while inflation-adjusted per pupil public school expenditures have increased by 80 percent since the early 1970s, SAT scores have plummeted from 937 in 1972 to 892 in 1995.  New York once exceeded the national average SAT score, but now trails considerably.      When you add in the high incidence of rape, robbery, drug abuse, teacher assault, and vandalism in schools, especially in the inner-city, as well as a dramatic increase in remedial courses at the college level designed to clean up English and math skills, it is clear our educational system, and America, is in trouble.     
<P>
The reason?  An educational monopoly, dominated by the world's most powerful special interests: the National Educational Association (NEA), the American Federation of Teachers (AFT), and here, the New York State United Teachers (NYSUT). The money these groups spend to maintain the status quo is staggering.  Indeed, in Albany, no other special interest group is better financed or wields greater power, over both Democrats and Republicans, than the education unions.     
<P>
Unlike people who work in private industry, where one must produce to make a living, the educational monopoly stifles performance.  Under collective bargaining, bad teachers are protected, good teachers receive no incentives.  What's worse, it's very hard to take a child out of the system.  Parents who look for a better educational product in our private schools still must pay once in taxes to fund the bad school and then once again in tuition.  Of course, public schools possess no incentives to cut costs.     
<P>
As we have found about New York, cost per pupil in public school districts can be astronomical.  The lowest cost in New York, based on 1992-93 figures, was $5,395 in the Portville school district.  But about half the districts in New York spend more than $8,000 annually, 25 percent spend more than $10,000, seven districts even spend more than $20,000, with two districts on Long Island -- Bridgehampton and Fire Island -- exceeding a whopping $31,000 per student!  Compare that with the average cost per pupil of private schools, somewhere around $3000.     
<P>
Giving parents a choice in education, through a system of vouchers or tax credits is the only way to break free from the educational monopoly, and renew American education.  And it is a proposal that is beginning to take hold across the country, what Milton Friedman sees as an impending tidal wave.  School choice plans are now in place in 20 states and the District of Columbia -- some privately financed and others through taxpayer dollars.       
<P>
In New York State, a bill called "The Elementary and Secondary Education Improvement Act" is now in committee.  While it still has a long way to go, signs are hopeful. C&K hears rumors that Governor Pataki supports school choice, and the Conservative Party has made choice part of it's Contract with New York for the fall elections.     Teachers' union officials have not yet launched a full scale assault on the bill, but according to sources in Albany, union lobbyists have been "dropping by" legislators' offices, hoping perhaps to strangle the bill in the cradle.  The growth in popularity of the measure must have them worried. Originally introduced in 1993 with only State Senator Serphin Maltese as a sponsor, the bill has grown each year, to its current level of 18 co-sponsors.     
<P>
Tim Mulhearn, of United New Yorkers for Choice in Education, and one of the architects of the bill, and Don Woods, of Citizens for Excellence in Education, think that once some minor changes are made to protect home schoolers and religious-school identity, the conservative coalition across New York will mobilize on behalf of the measure.     They also note, though, that this is not a conservative issue alone. Even some liberals like Assemblyman Dov Hikind are supporting the bill.  And why not?  Shouldn't everyone, not just the wealthy, have access to excellence in education?     As Milton Friedman notes, the private sector has done more to improve the standard of living in the last 200 years then all government could do in the previous 2000. It's time to completely unleash that power in education, as New York and America head into a challenging new era.
<P><br><i>
<center>
Matthew Carolan is executive editor of National Review. Raymond J. Keating is chief economist for the Small Business Survival Committee.</i>
<p><br>
| <a href="/sbsc/corner/corner.html">Keating's Corner</a> |</center>
<p> <br>
</BODY>
</HTML>
