		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  That was it.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- more in America.	<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  That was it.<p>

		And I was watching it on television --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Electric night.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  -- and I turned to my wife and
said, "It's over."<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  So did I.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

		So did I.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Yes.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  I said, "This is the beginning
of the end." <p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Second, marriage penalty -- you
all know the marriage penalty within the Code.  I won't
mention it to you.  It is a big problem in the double-income families.<p>

		All three of my children are double-income
families and will be so even if they don't afford it --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  -- because both halves have
career aspirations --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  -- and things that they want to
do in life. <p>

		And I think you have to do that.  And the
biggest problem with the marriage penalty now is on the
benefit side, where most benefits are "Use it or lose
it."  <p>

		And that is one of the many reasons we've gone
to a cafeteria plan, self-insurance, so that our
husband-and-wife combinations can get equity between
the two jobs.  There are a lot of ways to change that,
but that is a big, big problem.<p>

		Third, inheritance tax -- I think <p>

Mr. Thom has done the job on inheritance tax.  I must
tell you it is not -- this is not a problem for
corporations with 200 employees.  It is for him.  But
it is a giant problem for small businesses,
restaurants, farmers, and so forth and so on. <p>

		And I must also say that just because we're
focusing on small business, our large corporate friends
need tax relief as well.  So, don't forget that there
are big people out there.<p>

		Finally -- and this is the problem -- and that
is, where you stand on taxes depends on where you sit. 
And everybody is anti-tax, but all surveys show that,
in spite of what they say, they are pro-services from
government.  And it's a very difficult line to walk.<p>

		I do not believe successful tax relief can be
attained unless there is something done about overall
spending, because overall spending will ultimately, as
I've said in my testimony, jurisdictional shifts of tax
burdens which will then create an entrusting populace.  <p>

		So, I would urge you, as you do this, to see if
we can figure out some sort of a tax limitation,
whether it's Gross National Product related, gross
state product related -- there are different ways to
go.  We need to do capping on the spending side,
otherwise nobody will trust you underneath it.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Right.	<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  And to close on that and to
focus on the need of public education, my mother, rest
her soul, will forgive you for whoever spent my name
with a G.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Ah.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  Now, the person who did it
probably -- I think, knows me -- looked at my resume
for dozens of times where it says J -- her last name
was Jerald, that's where I got the name J -- and still
wrote G.  <p>

		And that's the same problem with the Tax Code. 
People have the fairness issue.  They have the "Tax the
other people."  They have the Russell Long "Don't tax
you, don't tax me, tax the man behind the tree." 
That's so in their mind that they will see things which
do not exist in taxes. <p>

		So, whatever you do, we need to have a very
strong --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Well said.<p>

		<b>DR. SCHENKEN:</b>:  -- national program.  <p>

		Thank you, sir.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Thank you.<p>

		Jerald with a J.<p>

		Jeff Renner is the principal officer of The
Freeman Company.<p>

		We're delighted Mr. Renner and look forward to
your testimony.<p>

		Do you want to move.<p>

		<b>MR. RENNER:</b>:  Yes.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Jerald with a J.<p>

		On behalf of Jack, Joanne, Jeffrey, Judith, and
Janice, I agree with you.<p>

		(Laughter)<p>

