end of the year.  <p>

		Now that we've lost income-averaging, farmers
and, I think, probably some small business, too, I'll
bet you Mr. Thom and his irrigation business, it goes
up and down some years.  But at least farmers have
tremendous shifts in income.  We've lost income-averaging.  We try to do it ourselves. <p>

		I do it by not selling hogs at the end of the
year, delaying till the next year, A lousy economic
decision, but a tax decision, and either buying or not
buying inputs in the first of the year to try to level
out my own income tax.<p>

		What, as a CPA -- and I presume you may do some
farmers' -- ranchers' returns, what do you -- how do
you assess this?  What do you do?  What do you think
