Mr. Chairman.<p>

		Gentlemen --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  "Death to the Tax Code."<p>

		COMMISSIONER PETERSON:  (Laughter)<p>

		Gentlemen, you were an absolutely superb panel. 
And I agree with Mr. Faris, we really should take you
on the road.  You were eloquent and right to the point.<p>

		One of the challenges that we will face as we
go forward with our assignment is trying to educate the
American people that it is possible to have both a
simple Tax Code and a fair Tax Code, because so often
in the past it has been argued or it has been assumed
that in order to be fair, it has to be complex; and
that in order to treat everybody precisely the same or
whatever, we have to, you know, create all these tiny
little rules to cover every possible piece of action.<p>

		And also, there has been some view in some
quarters that in order to be fair, that the rates have
to be -- we have to have multiple rates and that the
system has to be progressive.<p>

		So, I regard that as one of our greatest
challenges, and would welcome your views and your help
on how we might educate the American people to
understand that it is possible to have a system that is
simple, that doesn't address every kind of economic
circumstances, and yet it's also fair. <p>

		And I would welcome any comments that any of
you would like to make on that.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  I think one of the difficulties
we have is that the IRS has been one of the causes of a
major distrust of government.  <p>

