thank you for another export, and that is you provided
the Chargers, the Raiders, and the 49ers with some
great players, here from your football team.  <p>

		But what I'd like to focus on is the earlier
panels have addressed that as foreign companies have
brought their goods into our country, that they are
able to shed their local domestic taxes and the concept
is called border adjustability; but that when we export
our products overseas, that it carries with it a
burden, a tax burden that we cannot shed.  <p>

		And I'm interested in your thoughts, any view
on how that has impacted you, and to the extent that
this is an important part of any kind of tax reform.    <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Leroy.<p>

		MR. <b>MR. THOM:</b>  In the countries that we export, we
always talk about no tariffs -- you know, we're
supposed to be a free nation everywhere.  We only
export to one country that we don't bear a tariff, and
that's Israel.  All of the rest of them are as high
from 7 to <p>

25 percent.<p>

		The other thing that happens with many
countries, like Spain, for instance, anything they
offer to export, the government allows <p>

12 percent, gives them 12 percent of their product --
cost of their product.  And this makes it an unlevel
field.<p>

		It's a long way from a free trade world that we
are dreaming about here in the United States and have
dreamed about for 30 years.  And I don't think it's
ever going to come about.  		Now, maybe I'm wrong,
and I hope I'm wrong.  But I think we -- and I'm not
sure that government -- government just needs to get
off our back --<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.<p>

		MR. <b>MR. THOM:</b>  -- and let us go.  We'll fight some
of these other things.  <p>

		But, you know, in my 40 years in business, I
just can't believe the amount of stuff that comes down
the pike, the amount of people that I've got to have on
the payroll that don't produce anything except for the
government.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes.  Well said.<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Just a quick comment. <p>

		The answer to your question directly is yes,
we've got a deal with exports, especially Iowa and
Nebraska, but everybody.  <p>

		But I would make one comment.  Everybody talks
about the front-end load of this, the weight back home
of taxes and so on.  But I think they forget the front-end subsidies that go in to the production of whatever
is going overseas.<p>

		As you recall, America was not in GATT for
agriculture back -- originally, because the Americans
did not want agriculture covered with GATT.<p>

		So, I would, as you address this, which I hope
you do, be sure and look at the very strong political
problems dealing with the various front-end subsidies,
one country versus another, and see how we can smooth
the understanding of those out so that we can let Mr.
Thom sell his stuff without being beaten up on, which
he is right now.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  And in the interest of time,
it's -- the next panel should get prepared.<p>

		I want to thank the panel on behalf of our
Commission.  <p>

		Let me tell my fellow Commissioners, several of
the panelists either rearranged or changed -- or maybe
didn't give up, but made significant changes in their
vacation plans here in August.  <p>

		And we really appreciate -- not just the
passion, but the erudite, thoughtful, empirical,
personal evidence that you have brought before this
Commission.  <p>

		You've recharged us with the energy that never
flags, but sometimes it slows down a little bit.  <p>

		And I think Mr. Faris put it best, in thanking
each and every one of you for being here.    <p>

		Thanks, Frank and Leroy and --<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  Great job.<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  -- William and Dick and Jerald
with a J and Jeff with a G.<p>

		(Applause)	<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Yes, individuals can take a
break, but I want to move on to our next panel.<p>

		(Brief recess)		<p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  That was a non-break.<p>

