		John - Commissioner Wieland.  Question?<p>

		COMMISSIONER WIELAND:  Mr. Bettger said that he
had created several corporations to, you know, deal
with the issues that are out there.  And I wonder if
the rest of you -- is that what you have done, and is
that what other farmers have done generally?<p>

		PARTICIPANT:  We have not incorporated our
farm, because whenever we start getting into these
types of organizational changes, you've got to take
into considerations what it's going to do with your tax
bases of your land, how are you going to be able to
take your land back out.  		We visited with a
bunch of lawyers.  You can visit with a bunch of
accountants.  And it's very difficult to figure out
what needs to be done.  And after you're looking at
both issues, I'm not sure which way is the right way. 
And I get tired of paying the accountants and attorneys
trying to advise me.<p>

		<b>MR. BETTGER:</b>  As I mentioned, we did
incorporate our business in 1991, and I felt we were
forced into it.  We were looking at having two kids in
college for three years, and that amounts to more than
I, at one time, would have ever thought I could make.<p>

		When we were looking at trying to raise our
income, we were already at the point -- between
federal, Social Security, and state income taxes, we
were already paying at a rate of about 56 percent.  So,
any new dollar that we took in, we were only going to
be able to keep 44 percent.  <p>

		By incorporating and keeping land out of the
corporation, the corporation rents the land back.  And
we've eliminated the Social Security tax on the
investment that I mentioned earlier, and we are able to
deduct our health care.  <p>

		And there are a few things that it helps, but
it also creates double bookkeeping, it creates legal
fees, and there are also a lot of drawbacks.  <p>

		But like I said, I felt that we were forced
into it, not because we really wanted to do it.  <p>

		PARTICIPANT:  All right.  I incorporated in
1979.  The main reason was for tax management and debt
management. <p>

		<b>CHAIRMAN KEMP:</b>  Ted.<p>

