<HEAD>

<TITLE>Commission to Hold Final DC Hearing -- TRC</TITLE>

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0z Beta">
</HEAD>

<BODY>

<center><i>September 25, 1995</i>
<P>
<h3>TAX REFORM COMMISSION TO HOLD FINAL D.C. HEARING</h3>
</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<blockquote>
<I>Chairman Jack Kemp and other commissioners to
hear citizen testimony at Howard University</I>
</CENTER>

<P>
The importance of tax reform to economic growth,
jobs and entrepreneurship in our nation's urban areas will be
the highlight of a public hearing at Howard University in Washington,
D.C., on Tuesday, September 26, 1995, it was announced today by
Jack Kemp, chairman of the National Commission on Economic Growth
and Taxation.
<P>
The details of the hearing are:
<P>
Location: Blackburn Center, West Ballroom, Howard
University
<P>
  (Georgia Ave. and Howard Place entrance; parking
at 4th Street &amp; Bryant)
<P>
Time:  9:00 a.m. until 12:00 Noon, Tuesday, Sept.
26
<P>
  News availability with Chairman
Kemp, following the hearing, at 12:00 Noon.
<P>
Witnesses: Among those scheduled are:
<ul>
<li>  Steve Mariotti, President and CEO, National Foundation
for Teaching       Entrepreneurship.
<li>  Frank Almeda, a participant in the Natl. Foundation
for Teaching Entrepreneurship.
<li>  Michele Dyson, President and CEO, Computer Information
Specialist, Inc.
<li>  U.S. Rep. Linda Smith (R-WA), Chair, Tax and Finance
Subcommittee of      the Small Business Committee.
<li>  Barbara Franklin, Barbara Franklin Enterprises
(fmr. U.S. Commerce Secretary). 
</ul><P>
Background: The Howard University hearing continues
the Tax Reform Commission's (TRC) intent this month to conduct hearings in America's
inner cities, and focus on the    importance of access to capital,
credit and job opportunities in urban areas.  The    TRC has already
conducted hearings this month in South-central Los Angeles and  Harlem, New York City.  On Wednesday, Sept. 27,
the commission will convene for 
  its final public hearing in Cleveland, Ohio.
<P>  The 14-member TRC was appointed by Senate Majority
Leader Bob Dole and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who charged the commission
with making recommendations for a tax code that is &quot;flatter, fairer, and
simpler&quot; - a system that will encourage   economic growth and greater opportunity for all
Americans.  The commission plans to issue its final recommendations by the end of
1995.
<P>
</blockquote>
<P><P><font size="-1"><a href="/taxcom/prindex.html">PR Index</a> | <a href="/taxcom/">TRC Home</a> | <a href="/taxcom/reptoc.html">The Report</a></font></center><P></body>

