<title>USA Today Article</title>
</head>
<body>
<b>USA TODAY</b><br>
June 15, 1995
<p>
<center><b>KEMP STARTS TAX TALK:</b></center>
<p>
Former HUD secretary Jack Kemp opened the first meeting of a Republican tax
reform commission promising to give fair consideration to the full range of proposals for overhauling the tax code.  Kemp is a fan of a flat-rate income tax but said the 14-member commission, appointed by Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole, R-Kan., and House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga.,
would evaluate a wide variety of ideas.  In addition to a flat tax proposed by House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, he mentioned proposals for a consumption tax from Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee; a national sales tax from Sen. Dick Lugar, R-Ind.; and plans offered by House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., and Sen. Bill Bradley, D-NJ.
<p>
"It look partisan.  We're all men and women of the center-right of the spectrum" he said of the commission of business executives and former government officials "Ive taken stands, probably every one of us . . . has taken a stand on one sort of tax code or another. We're going to approach
It as open minded as we humanly, possibly, politically can."
<p>
