<head>
<title>The Washington Post Article</title>
</head>
<body>
<b>The Washington Post</b><br>
June 15, 1995
<p>
<center><h2>Tax Panel Head Vows Open-Mindedness</h2>
<p>
<h4>Kemp Says Members Will Consider Variety of Reform Options</h4>
<p>
By Dave Skidmore<br>
Associated Press</center>
<p>
Former housing secretary Jack Kemp opened the first meeting of a Republican tax reform commission
yesterday promising to give fair consideration to the full range of proposals for overhauling the tax code.
<p>
Kemp has advocated a flat-rate income tax, but said the 14-member commission, appointed by Senate
Majority Leader Robert J. Dole (R-Kan.) and House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.), would evaluate a 
wide variety of ideas.
<p>
In addition to a flat tax proposed by House Majority Leader Richard, K. Armey (R-Tex.), Kemp mentioned proposals for a consumption tax from House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill Archer (R-Tex.),  a national sales tax from Sen. Richard G. Lugar (R-lnd.) and plans offered by House Minority Leader  Richard A. Gephardt (D-Mo.) and Sen. Bill Bradley (D-NJ.).
<p>
"It looks partisan. We're an men and women of the center-right of the spectrum," Kemp said of the
commission of business executives and former government officials.  "I've taken stands, probably every one of us . . . has taken a stand on one sort of tax code or another. We're going to approach it as open minded as we humanly, possibly, politically can."
<p>
Dole and Gingrich asked Kemp to head the National Commission on Economic Growth and Tax Reform
two months ago and it is expected to issue its findings late this year, in time for the presidential primary 
elections.
<p>
"This . . . will be at the center of attention in '96 for the American people," Kemp said.
<p>
Republicans, who won control of Congress last year for the first time in four decades, are hoping to make tax reform as powerful an issue in 1996 as tax reduction was in 1994.
<p>
"If Congress just stops at reducing taxes, then it will not have finished its job," Dole said at a news
conference at the start of the commission meeting. "Americans . . . gave us control of Congress for the first time because they were fed up with the status quo. Now if theres one status quo that needs changing its the federal tax code."
<p>
