<h5>Volume 16, Number 3<br>Summer 1995</h5>
<h3><a name="contents">Contents</a></h3>
<a href="#sc"> Stunning Supreme Court Victory For Foundation Program Officer</a>
<br>
<a href="#rosen">Foundation Conference Examines Implications of Rosenberger Decision</a><br> 
<a href="#new">New Foundation Staffers Fresh from Campus Battle</a><br> 
<a href="#speak">Leftists Dominate Commencement Exercises</a><br> 
<a href="#about">About <i>Libertas</i></a><br>
<p><p><hr><p><p>
<a name="sc"><h3>Stunning Supreme Court Victory<br> For Foundation Program Officer<br></h3></a><h4>
Court finds University of Virginia Committed "Viewpoint Discrimination"</h4>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]<P></center></center>
<p>
On June 29, in a dramatic victory for students on campuses, the Supreme Court vindicated what conservatives have been arguing for years: universities are not permitted to treat religious speech as second class speech. In <i>Rosenberger v. Rector and the Visitors of the University of Virginia</I>, the Court determined that the University of Virginia discriminated against a Christian student newspaper when it denied the paper equal access to student activity fees. Young America's Foundation Program Officer <b>Ron Rosenberger</B>, who had founded the magazine, <i>Wide Awake</I>, while a student and Foundation activist at the University of Virginia, was the plaintiff in the case.
<p>
Mr. Rosenberger said, "The decision puts an end to the double standard used in university funding of student groups and guarantees a free marketplace of ideas on campuses across the country."
<p>
The Supreme Court case grew out of a 1991 decision by the University of Virginia to deny funds to a Christian publication due to its content. This decision came despite the fact that the university funded Jewish and Muslim groups on the basis of their being "cultural" activities. Funds were also granted to 116 other student groups, including Students for Animal Rights, the National Organization of Women, and several homosexual advocacy groups. Believing that he had been denied equal access to student activity fees,  Mr. Rosenberger, a Young America's Foundation activist, took his school to court.
<p>
The Supreme Court decided on the side of Christian students and Wide Awake. In a damning indictment of current university practices nationwide, Justice <B>Anthony M. Kennedy</b> wrote for the majority: "For the university, by regulation, to cast disapproval on particular viewpoints of its students risks the suppression of free speech and creative inquiry in one of the vital centers for nation's intellectual life, the college and university campuses."
<p>
Justice Kennedy argued that the most offensive aspect of UVa's position was that it monitored the content of student publications: "The viewpoint discrimination inherent in the university's regulation required public officials to scan and interpret student publications to discern their underlying philosophic assumptions reciting religious theory and belief.
<p>
"That course action," he continued, was a denial the right of be speech and would risk fostering
a pervasive bias or hostility to religion, which could undermine the very neutrality the Establishment Clause requires. There is no Establishment Clause violation in the University's honoring its duties under the Free Speech Clause."
<p>
In his dissent, Justice <b>David Souter</b> rationalized the university's position by stressing the religious content of the magazine. He quoted certain passages and cited the "frankly evangelistic character of the magazine" as justification for the university's actions.
<p>
Justice Kennedy took issue with the dissent, writing that Justice Souter's position would raise "the specter of governmental censorship, to ensure that all student writing and publications meet some baseline standard of secular orthodoxy. To impose that standard on student speech at a university is to imperil the very sources of free speech and expression.... official censorship would be far more inconsistent with the Establishment Clause's dictates than would governmental provision of secular printing services on a religion-blind basis."
<p>
In a concurring opinion, Justice <b>Clarence Thomas</b> wrote, "Though our Establishment Clause jurisprudence is in hopeless disarray, this case provides an opportunity to affirm one basic principle that has enjoyed an uncharacteristic degree of consensus: The Clause does not compel the exclusion of religious groups programs that are generally available to a broad class of participants."
<p>
Citing the intent of the Founding Fathers, Justice Thomas wrote, "The dissent identifies as evidence that the Framers intended to disable religious entities from participating on neutral terms in evenhanded government programs....Even if Madison believed that the principle of non-establishment of religion precluded government financial support for religion per se, there is no indication that at the time of the framing he took the dissent's extreme view that the government must discriminate against religious adherents by excluding them from more generally available financial subsidies."
<p>
Justice <b>Sandra Day O'Connor</b>, also concurring, wrote, "By withholding from Wide Awake assistance that the University provides generally to all other student publications, the University has discriminated on the
basis of the magazine's religious viewpoint in violation of the Free Speech Clause." Justice O'Connor relied on the principle of government's neutrality toward religion as the Court "held that schools may not discriminate against religious groups by denying them equal access to facilities that the schools make available to all."
<p>
She noted that widely divergent expressions of viewpoints are funded by the university, therefore there is no danger of any one opinion being perceived to be that of the university. She wrote, "Besides the general new publications, for example, the University has provided support to <I>The Yellow Journal</I>, a humor magazine that has targeted Christianity as a subject of satire, and <i>Al-Salam</I>, a publication to 'promote a better understanding of Islam to the University Community."'
<p>
Justice O'Connor opened the door to a challenge of the compulsory student activities fees "by an objecting student that she should not be compelled to pay for speech with which she disagrees."
<p><p><hr>
<p><p><center><a name="rosen"><h3>Foundation Conference Examines Implications<br>
of Rosenberger Decision</a></h3>
<h4>"Subdued Celebration" Urged In Wake of Supreme Court</h4>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]<P></center><P>
One day after the landmark Supreme Court decision supporting the rights of religious students on campus, over 125 students from more than 50 colleges and universities gathered in the nation's capital for a conference sponsored by Young America's Foundation. The conference, held on June 30, highlighted the case's ramifications for college students and informed campus activists of their rights of free speech on campus.
<p>
The lead plaintiff in the case, Foundation Program Officer <b>Ron Rosenberger</b>, opened the conference, saying, "The Supreme Court sent a message loud and clear that it is unconstitutional to treat religious students as second-class citizens or religious speech as second-class speech. Publicly funded colleges and universities will no longer be able to exclude religious groups from benefits that are made available to a wide array of student groups."
<p>
Two student panels, composed of students who have been subjected to similar harassment at their schools, spoke to conference attendees. <b>Bryson Koehler</b>, a student at the University of North Carolina and editor of the independent student newspaper there, the Carolina Review, related the tale of his magazine's defunding by the school. The school found the Review "to be politically partisan" due to a picture of Jefferson Davis in the paper. Ironically, the school funds the Daily Tar Heel which ran a page devoted to the endorsement of political candidates. The Daily Tar Heel has come under no scrutiny from the funding agencies of the school. Mr. Koehler will follow Ron Rose Iberger's example and take his case to the Federal District Court in North Carolina.
<p>
<b>Morgan Knull</b>, a junior at Wabash College in Indiana and an intern with Young America's Foundation, said students have to be willing to "stand up and face public ridicule. There will be other students who are sympathetic, but you have to go against the grain." He went on against the grain." He went on to say that at most campuses today, "Liberals are like vampires lurking around at night: You have to expose them."
<p>
Mr. Knull told of the abuse with which religious students must contend at Wabash. The professor of a course in human sexuality showed the movie, 120 Days of Sodom, to his class and others "as a statement against the religious right." The movie, which has been banned in Italy and France for its obscenity, was deemed appropriate and necessary for students to view by the leftist professor. Mr. Knull stood up to his professor and challenged the appropriateness of the movie being shown in class. After bringing Mr. Knull up on harassment charges, the professor eventually dropped all charges and admitted that he should not have shown the film.
<p>
Mr. Knull exhorted students: "Don't water down your beliefs. I stand up for what I believe in because I love my school and want it to become again the institution of academic vigor that it used to be. Take your message outside your school if you need to.  Get involved with national groups which can help you, such as Young America's Foundation."
<p>
Syndicated columnist <b>Joseph Sobran</b> spoke to the conference, giving students a sobering perspective on the significance of the Rosenberger decision in its jurisprudence and historical context. He said many of the current problems conservative students face stem from the 16th Amendment which gave the federal government the power to levy income taxes. He said, "Direct taxing power gave enormous power to the federal government and, in effect, neutralized the rest of the Constitution." The Rosenberger decision, he said, was a ''tactical victory. . . . In this case, the federal government is still telling the state what it can and cannot do."
<p>
According to Mr. Sobran, "Education was compromised and corrupted once it became a state function. We should insist that religious people be given the same treatment as everyone." He concluded, "Let's have a subdued celebration in this victory and push on for a return to true federalism."
<p>
The 1995 Henry Salvatori Distinguished Lecturer, <b>M. Stanton Evans</b>, gave the closing remarks, saying that the Rosenberger victory is "one of the most important Supreme Court decisions in constitutional history." He said the decision challenged a 1947 decision by Justice Black which stated that the government may provide no support whatsoever for any religious sentiment. It is not possible, however, to "reconcile Black's decision with the activities of the Founding Fathers. Everything he says you shouldn't do, they were doing."
<p>
The purpose of the First Amendment, Mr. Evans said, "had nothing to do with Black's statement. It was intended to protect the states from intrusion by the federal government."
<p>
Young America's Foundation will continue to educate students about their religious and free speech rights on campus as a result of the Rosenberger decision.
<p><p><hr><p><p><center><a name="new">
<h3>New Foundation Staffers Fresh From Campus Battle<br></a>
Kingsley, Schenk Return To Foundation</h3>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
Anxious to find an alternative to the liberal monopoly on campus, students are discovering that Young America's Foundation is the organization best able to provide that alternative through its celebrated speakers program and vast campus outreach network. In response to the increased volume of student requests for Foundation support and information, Young America's Foundation has added two new program officers to assist with campus outreach.
<p>
<b>Kristen Kingsley</b> and <b>Matthew Schenk</b>, both conservative activists, are fresh from the front-lines of the great clash of ideas taking place on the nation's campuses. Both served as interns for the Foundation during the summer of 1994, when Miss Kingsley organized the National Conservative Student Summer Conference, ant Mr. Schenk produced the Foundation's 25th Anniversary Report.
<p>
Mr. Schenk joined the Foundation's staff in June as a program officer, after graduating in May from Swarthmore College with a B.A. in English literature and political science. He served as editor-in-chief of Swarthmore's main student newspaper, The Phoenix, earning the distinction of being the first sophomore to ever hold that position. He also co-founded the Swarthmore College Republicans, and worked for <b>Rick Santorum's</b> 1994 Senate campaign.
<p>
Mr. Schenk became an ardent campus activist in the fall of 1993 when, with Young America's Foundation's assistance, he helped found the Swarthmore Conservative Union. The Foundation, recognizing Mr. Schenk's ability to contribute significantly to campus conservatism, assisted him in establishing an independent campus newspaper, Common Sense, with the goal of "providing an open and friendly forum for conservative views at Swarthmore." In his last two years at Swarthmore, Mr. Schenk and other campus activists brought nine Foundation speakers to this historically liberal college, including <b>William F. Buckley, Dinesh D'Souza, Star Parker</B>, and <b>Phyllis Schlafly</b>.
<p>
Mr. Schenk will use the experience he gained at Swarthmore to help students at other colleges get their message across. "I had so much fun creating controversy on campus during my four years at college," he admits, "I decided I wanted to make a career out of it."
<p>
The kind of "controversy" Mr. Schenk incited included a successful campaign to raise the American flag over the main building at Swarthmore, where it had been absent for the past 30 years. He also aroused the anger of the Swarthmore liberal establishment when he chartered a gun club dubbed SAFER: Swarthmore Advocates of Firearm Education and Recreation and pressured the college's budget committee into funding the group's outings. After only one year, SAFER has become the second largest recreational organization at Swarthmore.
<p>
Still, Mr. Schenk and his conservative allies at Swarthmore had an uphill battle to have their voices heard on a college that prides itself for "tolerance" and "diversity." The Swarthmore conservatives ran into many obstacles created by the liberal administration and student groups, and they achieved little success before Young America's Foundation took on their cause. "The Foundation's help really turned things around for us on campus, " Mr. Schenk said. After attending and helping to organize the Foundation's 1994 Summer I Conference as an intern, he decided that this was the kind of work to which he wanted to dedicate himself.
<p>
"There is no one on college campuses today who is as oppressed as the conservative student," Mr. Schenk points out. "And there is no group that does more to help these students than Young America's Foundation.
<p>
"We would not have had the impact we did at Swarthmore without the invaluable support of the Foundation," he adds. "Now, as a part of the Foundation's staff, I hope I can help other students make the same difference an their campuses."
<p>
Miss Kingsley's commitment to campus conservatism and her contagious enthusiasm make her a valuable addition to the staff. She believes this is a critical time for campus conservatism: "The whole country is becoming increasingly receptive to the traditional, free-market ideas that Young America's Foundation has advocated for over 25 years. Nowhere is this more true than on college campuses, where students have grown tired of the politically correct, socialist bias that their professors bring into the classroom on a daily basis."
<p>
Miss Kingsley, an Alabama native, joined the Foundation staff in June as a program officer and director of the National Conservative Student Conference. Since her arrival at the Foundation, Miss Kingsley coordinated the 17th Annual National Conservative Student Conference, held in Washington, D.C. in late July. The conference was an overwhelming success with over 400 students attending. With her outstanding interpersonal and organizational skills, Miss Kingsley will organize regional student conferences, including those to be held in Atlanta and Chicago during the school year.
<p>
For Miss Kingsley, the idea of planning such conferences is an appealing challenge: "I am anxious to work with speakers and students across the country as the Foundation continues its tradition of hosting the most effective regional student conferences in the nation." She believes that "exposing students in person to the ideas espoused by top national leaders is the most effective means of swelling the conservative ranks."
<p>
In May, 1995, Miss Kingsley graduated cum laude from Wake Forest University with a B.A. in politics and speech communication, and was inducted into honor societies in both S fields. An activist during her college years, Miss Kingsley attended the Foundation's 1993 National Summer Conference, and the spring of  1995, brought the foundation's Henry Salvatori lecturer, <b>Stan Evans</b>, to speak at Wake Forest. During the 1992 election, Miss Kingsley served <b>President Bush's</b> North Carolina advance team, and she volunteered for the campaigns of Congressman <b>Richard Burr</b> and Senator <b>Lauch Faircloth</b>.
<p>
In addition to being one of the nation's foremost campus activists and a stellar student, Miss Kingsley served as chairman of freshman orientation, a member of the student government legislature, a campus tour guide, an elementary school tutor, and even as a disc jockey on the campus radio station.
<p><p><HR><p><p><center><a name="speak"><h3>Leftists Dominate Commencement Exercises<br></a>
Shalala, Steinem, Edelman Top List of Speakers</h3>
[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]</center><P>
College graduation ceremonies are called "commencements" because they mark the beginning of post-college life. But in recent years college administrators are using the commencement ceremonies to send their students off with one more predictable Leftist lecture. In 1995, commencement exercises were dominated by Congressional Democrats, liberal media personalities, and Clinton Administration officials.
<p>
College administrators are reluctant to release lists of guest lecturers on their campuses because they fear criticism of their almost exclusively liberal line-up of speakers. However, commencement exercises are open to the general public and the identity of the guest speaker is obtainable. A survey of commencement addresses was conducted by Young America's Foundation of the nation's one hundred most selective colleges according to James Cass and Max Birnbaum's <i>Comparative Guide to American Colleges</I>. The results provide another insight into how our colleges offer an unbalanced view of our culture and public affairs. Instead of providing a new beginning, the commencement exercises continue the liberal bias that makes up much of a four year undergraduate education.
<p>
College administrators are enthralled with media and entertainment celebrities. National Public Radio's 
<B>Daniel Shorr</b> (Brandeis), CNN's <B>Catherine Crier</B> (Lehigh), AP's <b>Helen Thomas</b> (American), New York Times columnist <b>Russell Baker</b> (Connecticut College), CBS' <b>Dan Rather</b> (University of Texas), Washington Post columnist <b>William Raspberry</b> (University of Virginia), and ABC's <b>Ted Koppel</b> (Johns Hopkins) were among a long list of featured media personalities.
<p>
<b>Robert Redford and Quincy Jones</b> were Pomona's choices, <b>Barbra Streisand</b> joined Daniel Shorr as Honorary Degree recipients at Brandeis, and <b>Lynn Redgrave</b> was Centre College's commencement speaker.
<p>
Elected officials, at least if they are Democrats, are popular with the college administrators . President <b>Bill Clinton</b> addressed graduates at Dartmouth College. Congressman <b>George Brown</b> spoke at Claremont's Harvey Mudd, Congresswoman <b>Barbara Kennelly</b> at Trinity, Senator <b>Bill Bradley</b> at Rice, and Baltimore Mayor <b>Curt Schmoke</b> at Yale. The only Republican office holder to show up on this year's list was Congressman <b>Bob Livingston</b> at his alma mater, Tulane.
<p>
Clinton Administration officials made up the largest category of commencement speakers. Government officials were seldom invited during the Reagan-Bush years, indeed government critics dominated the list, but Clinton Administration officials are now welcomed with open arms.
<p>
Clinton's HHS Secretary <b>Donna Shalala</b> spoke at Syracuse University, Budget Director <b>Alice Rivlin</b> at the University of Iowa, Energy Czar <b>Hazel O'Leary</b> at Vassar, and Economic Advisor <b>Laura Tyson</b> at American University. Clinton's UN Ambassador <b>Madeline Albright</b> was the choice of Wellesley, Barnard, and the University of Michigan.  Defense Secretary <b>William Perry</b> spoke at Stanford University and Penn State, and NEA Chair <b>Jane Alexander</b> spoke at the University of Pennsylvania.
<p>
Other Clinton associates chosen include <b>Vernon Jordan</b> by Colgate, <b>Johnnetta Cole</b> by Oberlin, and <b>David Gergen</b> by Duke. Former Texas Governor <b>Ann Richards</b> spoke at Mount Holyoke.
<p>
Liberal activists were among those honored in this year's commencement exercises, including <b>Gloria Steinem</b> at Smith, Children's Defense Fund President <b>Marian Wright Edelman</b> at the University of Virginia and Occidental College, and Urban League official <b>Hugh Price</b> at George Washington.
<p>
Young America's Foundation's annual survey highlights an independently chosen list of highly selective colleges. The Leftist and pro-Clinton trends, however, are not exclusive to this group. The <i>New York Times</i> reported that the top four "Honored and Honored" choices found in its more comprehensive survey were: <B>Marian Wright Edelman</b> (seven honorary degrees or Commencement lectures), <b>Henry Louis Gates, Jr.</b> (six), <b>Bill Cosby</b> (six), and Donna Shalala (four). Commencement speakers at less selective schools also emphasized anti-Republican and pro-big government themes.
<p>
And a year-by-year comparison reinforces the bias. For example, the honored guests invited to George Washington University during the past three years included Donna Shalala ('93), <b>Hillary Clinton</b> ('94) and <b>Tom Foley</b> ('95) Yale honored <b>Jodie Foster</b> in 1993, <b>Sargent Shriver</b> in 1994 and Democrat Mayor Curt Schmoke in 1995. The University of Pennsylvania hosted Hillary Clinton (93), <b>Henry Cisneros</b> ('94), and Jane Alexander ('95).  Stanford's 1993 speaker was <b>Diane Feinstein</b>, 1994 speaker was <b>Stephen Carter</b>, and this year it was William Perry. Dartmouth chose <b>Bill Moyers</b> in 1993, Robert Reich in 1994.  Reich's boss Bill Clinton in 1995. Duke's last three speakers were Bill Bradley, Judy Woodruff, and David Gergen. Wellesley sticks with Liberal women: Gloria Steinem, <b>Cokie Roberts</b>, and Madeline Albright.
<p>
In a by-gone era college administrators were reluctant to have Leftists and Democrat politicians dominate their commencement exercises because parents, trustees, and donors were on hand. But in recent years those inhibitions vanished on most campuses. Clinton Administration officials, Liberal commentators, and elected Democrat officials are regularly given the honor of addressing the graduating seniors and their families.
<p>
This imbalance appears especially acute in a year when college students demonstrated their strong preference for conservative speakers when they were available. <b>Bill Bennett, William F. Buckley, Jr., P.J. O'Rourke, Oliver North, Margaret Thatcher</b>, and <b>General Colin Powell</b> drew standing room only crowds on many campuses during the school year. In nearly every case they spoke before much larger audiences than their liberal counter parts. In addition, in a year when revolutionary changes came to Capitol Hill, the major campuses' graduates didn't hear from a single member of the new Republican leadership.
<p>
Some Republicans and a couple of conservatives were among the speakers at the major campuses. Yet they are invariably former officials who are unlikely to champion a conservative position on today's cutting-edge issues in a manner comparable to that of the Democratic office-holders who are actively defending the Clinton Administration positions. President <b>George Bush</b> delivered the commencement address at William and Mary, <b>Marilyn Quayle</b> spoke at Rose Hulman Institute of Technology in Indiana, and Stanford Administrator <b>Condoleezza Rice</b> was honored at Notre Dame.
<p>
Harvard's Commencement speaker was Czech Republic President <b>Vaclav Havel</b>.
<p>
No conservative movement organization leader, free market academic, Reagan appointed jurist, or conservative religious leader, addressed any of the top schools' commencements. Outstanding speakers such as Nobel Laureate <b>Milton Friedman</b>, Stanford scholar <b>Thomas Sowell</b>, author Clancy, Rev. <b>Billy Graham</b>, Cardinal <B>John O'Connor</b>, General <B>Norman Schwarzkopf</b>, media commentators <b>George Will</b> and <B>Rush Limbaugh</b>, and House leaders <B>Newt Gingrich</b> and <B>Dick Armey</b>, were passed over for the likes of Gloria Steinem, Lynn Redgrave, Daniel Shorr, and back bench Democrat Congressmen!
<p>
Commencements this year looked more like one last dose of left-wing indoctrination than a fresh start for the graduates of the Class of '95.
<p><p>

