<CENTER><H3>Arm  Yourself  With  Ideas</H3>
Social Security, Financial Aid Issue Briefs Available<BR></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
Have you ever been in a 
     class and had your professor or a classmate go on and on expounding some 
liberal position?  Perhaps you wanted to challenge their arguments but 
were reluctant because you didn't have all the facts on hand.  
Young America's Foundation would like to help.
<P>The Foundation understands that conservative ideas are 
rarely mentioned in the classroom unless they are being distorted by a 
professor.  It is easy for students to come across the liberal 
arguments in their classes, in casual discussions, or in the campus paper.  
In order to learn about conservative ideas, however, students need 
to go out of the way, taking the initiative and doing their own research.  
<P>The Foundation recognizes that getting a balanced 
education <I>shouldn't </I>be such a time consuming project.  To help students 
learn about the <I>other </I>side of the argument, Young America's 
Foundation is continuing its series of &quot;issue briefs&quot; on the most 
controversial and hotly debated issues on campus.  
<P>The latest two issue briefs provide valuable information on 
the issues of Social Security privatization and reform of 
the student financial aid system.  These are two issues that should be 
of optimum concern to college-aged students.  With the 
information provided by these two briefs, you will be able to challenge 
liberal professors, misguided classmates, and slanted editorials.
<P>In addition to the &quot;Social Security&quot; and &quot;Financial Aid&quot; 
issue papers, the Foundation is still offering its brief covering 
&quot;Affirmative Action on Campus.&quot;  If you would like to receive copies of 
 these informative papers, please contact <B>Matthew Schenk 
</B>at Young America's Foundation at 1-800-292-9231.
<P>
<HR>
<a name="novak">
