<BR> 
<H3>Terry Eastland to Deliver 1996-97 Hermann Lectures</H3><BR>
<B>Terry Eastland</B>, author of 
<I>     Ending Affirmative Action: 
     The Case for Colorblind Justice</I>, will be the featured 
speaker of the Foundation's <B>Grover Hermann Freedom Lecture 
Series</B> for the 1996-1997 academic year. 
<table align=right width="200" hspace="5">
<tr><td><IMG SRC="eastland.gif" WIDTH=150 HEIGHT=206><BR>
<B><I>Terry Eastland</B>, 1996-97 Grover Hermann Lecturer.
</td></tr>
</table>  
Mr. Eastland offers a 
compelling criticism of race-based quotas and rigged admissions 
policies.  He argues that the true test of a democracy is its adherence 
to colorblindness. 
<P>Mr. Eastland is editor of <I>Forbes 
MediaCritic</I> and a fellow at the <BR>
Ethics and Public Policy Center in Washington, D.C.  He is a 
leading authority on Supreme Court decisions concerning not only race 
but also religious freedom.  His research and experience give him 
a unique perspective on the impact of affirmative action.  
<P>The Grover Hermann Freedom Lecture Series was named 
in memory of the entrepreneur, <B>Grover 
Hermann</B>.  As founder of American Asphalt Company 
and chairman of the board of Martin Marietta Corporation until 
his death in 1979, Mr. Hermann was remembered as a man who 
generously contributed both his time and fortune to many 
philanthropies.
<P>To bring Mr. Eastland to speak on your campus, call 
<B>Stephen Slivinski</B> at 1-800-292-9231.
<P>
<HR>
<a name="screw">
<P>
<BR>
<a href="#contents">Table of Contents</a>
<BR>
<H3>Are There &quot;Screwballs, Devil Dames, and 
Closet Cases&quot; in Your College's Curriculum?</H3>
Young America's Founda
          tion has just completed the 
          second edition of <I>Comedy and Tragedy:  College Course 
Descriptions and What They Tell Us About Higher Education 
Today</I>.
<P>This edition examines courses from fifty national 
universities and liberal arts colleges and concludes that bizarre 
and trendy courses have infiltrated every facet of higher 
education.
<P>To many, courses such as Harvard's &quot;A Thousand 
Feminisms,&quot; De Paul's &quot;Sociology of Rock Music,&quot; 
and Amherst's &quot;Black English&quot; are 
merely amusing, but college students understand that the 
product of this kind of frivolous, &quot;multicultural&quot; curriculum is 
an inferior education and poor preparation for the job market.
<P>Parents, taxpayers, concerned educators, and prospective employers should also be troubled 
by this tragedy in American higher education.  Due to this 
obsession with multiculturalism and &quot;victim studies,&quot; an entire generation 
of students is being ill-prepared for life in the real world.
<P><I>Comedy and Tragedy </I>reveals that courses such as 
&quot;Sorcery and Magic,&quot; and &quot;Sex and Gender on Film: 
Screwballs, Devil Dames, and Closet Cases,&quot; are just the tip of 
the iceberg.  
<P>
<BR>
To order this in-depth study of the modern 
college curriculum, contact <B>Dede Hamilton </B>at 1-800-292-9231. <HR>
<P>
