<a name="foundation"><center><h3>Foundation to Liberate the Left Coast!<br></h3></a>
<h4>Western Leadership Conference Set for April 12-13!</h4></center>

<p>Young America's Foundation is proud to announce its <B>Western Leadership Conference:  Call to Action</B> will be held <B>April 12-13</B> at the 
<B>Atrium Hotel</B> in <B>Irvine, California</B>.  Full-time students are invited 
to attend free of charge, but you <I>must</I> register in advance.
<P>Inspirational and informative speakers include Lt. Colonel <B>Oliver North</B>, Judge <B>William Clark</B>, talk radio host <B>Armstrong Williams</B>, Foundation president <B>Ron Robinson</B>, author <B>Dinesh D'Souza</B>, and economist 
<B>Walter Williams</B>. 
<P>In addition to hearing from these national leaders, you will also receive effective training geared to help you defend your beliefs in the hostile setting of today's campus.
<P>This exciting two-day conference is a great way to meet right-minded students from other universities and to network within the Conservative Movement.  Impressed with the line-up of speakers at the Foundation's regional conference in Atlanta, Florida sophomore Jackie Stevens exclaimed, "I missed many of the ideas of 
conservatism in my education, and that is what I am getting here at this conference."
<P>Don't miss <I>your</I> opportunity to meet and hear top conservative leaders on April 12-13:  call <B>Kristen Kingsley</B> at 1-800-292-9231 for your registration form!
<HR><P><P>
<center>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]<P></center>
<p><p>



<a name="summer"><center><h3>D.C. Summer Conference Set for July 21-27!<br></h3></center></a>

If you believe that your liberal professors are giving you a less-than-balanced education, you need to attend Young America's Foundation's 18th annual 
<B>National Conservative Student Conference</B> at <B>George Washington University</B> on <B>July 21-27</B>.  Campus activists from across the U.S. will gather in our nation's capital to hear from top public policy figures, leading journalists and commentators, and key Movement leaders.
<P>Receiving<B> C-SPAN</B> coverage for the last three years, recent conference speakers included <B>Jack Kemp</B>, <B>Bill Bennett</B>, <B>Ed Meese</B>, <B>Walter Williams</B>, <B>Robert Novak</B>, <B>Fred Barnes</B>, <B>Bay Buchanan</B>, <B>Dinesh D'Souza,</B> MTV's <B>Kennedy</B>, <B>Oliver 
North</B>, and <B>Ralph Reed</B>.  Students are treated to an annual Capitol Hill briefing featuring Congressmen such as <b>Dick Armey, Sony Bono, Charles Stenholm</b>, and <b>Bob Dornan</b> as well as Senators such as <b>Trent Lott, Phil Gramm</b>, and <b>Jesse Helms</b>. House Speaker <b>Newt Gingrich</b> has addressed the conference every year for the past five years, last summer's group was especially honored to have a private lunch with the Speaker of the House.
<p>This intensive, week-long conference provides an unparalleled opportunity for students to experience the Conservative Movement while expanding their knowledge of free-market economics, American history, and a host of contemporary issues.
<p>For more information or to receive an application to attend the 1996 National Conservative Student Conference, call <b>Kristen Kingsley</b> at 1-800-292-9231 today! 
<HR><P><P>
<center>[ <a href="#contents">Contents</a> ]<P></center>
<p><p>

<a name="monopoly"><center><h3>Fight the Liberal Monoply on Your Campus<br></h3></center></a>

Most American college campuses are in desperate need of reform.  At a time when      the American people are rejecting big government and the whole world is rejecting socialism, most campus economics and political science departments still cling to the failed policies of  Marxism.  Speech codes, designed to silence politically incorrect views, are in effect at hundreds of colleges and universities.  Campus curricula is overwhelmingly slanted to the left in virtually every subject, as victim-studies courses have crowded out more traditional offerings in many fields.  Faculty and administrators almost exclusively reserve guest lecture invitations to radical Leftists.  If students wish to bring conservative or free market speakers to their campuses, they must do so on their own.
<P>There is much at stake here.  If Leftist ideas are allowed to go unchallenged on campus, then they alone will influence and educate our nation's future leaders.  Your professors and administrators--the radicals and rabble-rousers of the 1960s--are not likely to promote traditional and free market ideas.  It is the students who are the greatest hope for reforming this imbalance.
<P>If you are a student on today's campus, you are at the very point of conflict in a cultural and intellectual war to determine the future of American society.  You, your children, and your grandchildren will live in a country substantially impacted by the outcome of that struggle.
<P>Young America's Foundation is here to help you in this struggle.  We provide the resources that can help you balance the campus debate.  In addition to our extensive campus lecture program, we also can provide you with advice on how to become a more effective campus reformer.  An informative guide, entitled <B><I>A Student Strategy for Campus Reform</B></I>, has recently been published by Young America's Foundation.  In this guide, you will find advice on how to form a campus organization, obtain funding for speakers and activities, inform sympathetic alumni of your efforts, and get coverage from campus and local media.
<P>In reforming your campus, you are not only doing a great service for your fellow students and your country, but you are also developing skills and connections that will benefit you for years to come.  You could have the opportunity to meet public figures and personalities such as <B>William F. Buckley, Jr., Walter Williams</B>, and <B>Margaret Thatcher </B>when you arrange for them to lecture at your campus.  Your group may even be featured by the local newspaper or even in the national media if your campaign attracts public attention, as has been the case with 
many students who undertake the goal of campus reform.
<P>If you would like to receive the <B><I>Student Strategy for Campus 
Reform</B></I>, or if you would like any information on the many other programs offered by Young America's Foundation, please call 1-800-292-9231.

<HR><P><P>
