<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Heritage Foundation Internship Program -- Intern Projects</TITLE>
<BODY BGCOLOR="F5F5F5">
<CENTER>
<FONT FACE="GENEVA" COLOR="RED"><H1>HERITAGE INTERNSHIP<BR>
PROGRAM</H1></FONT>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="learn.gif" WIDTH=291 HEIGHT=31 BORDER=0 ALT="Learn Today, Lead Tomorrow">
</CENTER>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=0 ALIGN=LEFT CELLPADDING=5 CELLSPACING=5>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=120>

<P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/applictn.html"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/app.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Application button"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/program.html"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/pro.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Program button"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/resources.html"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/resource.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Resource button"></A><P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/projects.html"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/proj.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Projects button"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/96interns.gif"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/photo.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Picture button"></A>
<P>
<A HREF="/heritage/intern_program/alumni.html"><IMG SRC="/heritage/intern_program/alum.gif" WIDTH=108 HEIGHT=55 BORDER=0 ALT="Alumni button"></A>
</TD></TR></TABLE>

<TABLE BORDER=0 WIDTH=500 CELLPADDING=15 CELLSPACING=15>
<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER><FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="RED"><H3>HERITAGE INTERN PROJECTS</H3></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<DD>
Like any other internship in Washington, interns assist analysts and staff with day-to-day support work such as retrieving articles from The Library of Congress, picking up a memo from a Capitol Hill committee, or mailing out Heritage papers.  What makes Heritage different, however, is that in addition to administrative tasks, every intern is assigned to an analyst or staff member to guide them in research and projects, monitor the intern's work, and make sure that they are challenged in their internship.
<P>
<DD>
Here are just a few of the projects the 1996 interns worked on:
<P>
<UL>
 <LI>Emily Stimpson, a rising senior and Political Science major at Miami University, interned for Coalition Relations and helped to update <I>The Guide to Public Policy Experts</I>.  She also assisted Doug Seay, Director of The Federalism Project, with research for his upcoming paper on federalism and the courts.
 <P>
 <LI>Ryan Rusak, a rising junior and Journalism major at Texas Christian University, and the 1996 recipient of the Lawrence Wade Journalism Fellowship, aided the Public Relations Department with the weekly Heritage in The News clip sheet.  Rusak also wrote an op-ed on the liberal media bias, which was nationally distributed and printed in some of the smaller daily and weekly papers across the country. Rusak also aided the department by answering media queries.
 <P>
 <LI>
 Tyce Palmaffy, a rising senior at The University of Virginia and Economics major, worked the <I>Policy Review</I> staff this summer.  Palmaffy was assigned to investigating the effects of repealing the National Maximum Speed Limit Law, which dates back to 1974.  His efforts resulted in publishing an article for the Laboratories of Democracy section for the September/October issue of <I>Policy Review</I> titled <A HREF="/heritage/p_review/sept96/labs.html">"Don't Brake for Government."</A> 
 <P>
 <LI>Matthew Clay, a rising junior and Government major at Georgetown University, interned for <A HREF="/townhall"><I>Town Hall, Inc.</I></A> and was an integral part of staff working to design homepagees for the various groups that are a part of <I>Town Hall</I> such as <A HREF="/conservative">The American Conservative Union</A>, <A HREF="/empower">Empower America</A>, and <A HREF="/frc">The Family Research Council</A>.  Clay wrote programs that will create more interaction between the groups by linking the pages to other sites.
 <P>
 <LI>Tammy Meyer, a rising senior and Political Science major at Duke University, was the research assistant for the National Security staff at Heritage.  During her summer stay, Tammy helped arrange a major civil-military relations symposium at Heritage, and wrote the conference proceedings as well.  She also headed the research effort into the national security chapters of 1997 version of The Heritage Foundation's <A HREF="/heritage/mandate/"><I>Mandate for Leadership</I></A>, a guide to implementing conservative policies in the government.  Her work for this book focused on budget priorities in the Department of Defense, national military strategy, and the role of the U.S. in regional military alliances.
 <P>
 <LI>Stephanie Kish, an Echols Scholar and a Government and Foreign Affairs major, graduated from The University of Virginia in May.  Kish interned with Edwin Meese III, where she worked on several projects.  Kish helped General Meese track crime patterns over the last fifty years by researching crime statistics from the Library of Congress.  She also helped reset crime periodicals for an upcoming Blueprint on Crime.  Kish also helped General Meese and his staff monitor the 1996 Supreme Court  term for criminal and constitutional law decisions.  Kish will attend Indiana University School of Law in the Fall on a full academic scholarship.
 <P>
 <LI>Kristen Layman, entering the public policy graduate program at The University of Rochester, fall 1996, did research for <A HREF="/heritage/staff/antonel.htm">Angela Antonelli</A> on FDA reform; Her research will contribute to a chapter devoted to regulatory reform in Heritage's upcoming <A HREF="/heritage/mandate/"><I>Mandate for Leadership</I></A>.  Layman also analyzed regulations in the Federal Register and the Unified Agenda to see if they remain consistent with Clinton's plan to reinvent government.
 
 <P>
 <LI>Patrick Roberts, a rising senior and politics major at The University of Dallas, interned for Bradley fellows Jim Payne and John Miller.  He assisted Payne in publishing his upcoming book on Octavia Hill's collection of essays on welfare reform.  Roberts aided Miller in gathering statistics for his upcoming book on assimilation and immigration.  He will be the editor of <I>The University News</I> this year at The University of Dallas.
 
 <P>
 <LI>Brad Gillen, a rising senior and Government major at Hampden-Sydney College, worked as a research assistant for Executive Branch Liaison Karen Miller.  One of Brad's responsibilities was working on Karen's <A HREF="/heritage/cyberwel.html">Cyber-Personality</A> site on Heritage's home page, researching issues and helping answer e-mail about Heritage's work.  Brad also helped Karen respond to presidential candidate requests for Heritage information and papers.
</UL>
<P>
</TD></TR></TABLE>
