<TR>
<TD VALIGN=TOP>
<CENTER><FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="RED"><H3>HERITAGE AT WORK</H3></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<DD><B>Leadership:</B> Heritage was founded in 1973 "to formulate and promote conservative public policies based on the principles of free enterprise, limited government, individual freedom, traditional family values, and a strong national defense."  A non-partisan tax-exempt institution, it is now one of the most influential research and education foundations in the United States, providing national, state, and local decision makers with concise information relevant to current policy debates.

<P>
<DD>
<B>Ideas: </B> Congress turns to Heritage as a major source of fresh ideas in legislative debates over welfare reform, overhauling the tax code, the 1995 budget debate, and other important public policy questions.  Heritage was instrumental, for instance, in proposing the $500 per-child tax credit as a way to strengthen parents in raising their children.  Heritage publishes 250+ papers and studies every year proposing conservative reform ideas.

<P>
<DD>
<B>Education:</B> Heritage is first and foremost an educational institution.  We educate policy makers about the issues and questions before them.  We also seek to educate students, conservative activists and the public through seminars, debates and lectures by speakers such as Steve Forbes, Ralph Reed, and Dick Armey.  The Heritage Internship Program is an integral part of our educational activities. 
<P>

<BLOCKQUOTE>
<I>"Heritage is not only interested in shaping the current political debate, but also influencing those who will be framing the debate in the next century." </I>
<P>
<B>Dr. Edwin J. Feulner, Jr.,</B><BR>
President, The Heritage Foundation
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>

<FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="BLUE"><B>Interns at Work Today</B></FONT>


