<P>
Heritage Encourages Young Conservatives to....

<P>
<FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="BLUE"><B>INVESTIGATE...</B></FONT>
<P>
<DD>
Interns gain <B>solid experience</B> conducting research for Heritage senior fellows, attending congressional briefings, and designing web-pages for Heritage's Internet site.  During his summer internship with <I>Policy Review</I>, Tyce Palmaffy wrote <A HREF="/heritage/p_review/sept96/labs.html">"Don't Brake for Big Government,"</A> for the magazine's Sept./October 1996 issue.

<P>
<FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="BLUE"><B>
EXPLORE... </B></FONT>

<P>
<DD>
Interns study the origins of conservative thought and the principles of American government in <B>reading groups</B> led by Educational Affairs staff.  Reading selections range from Aristotle and Machiavelli, to Washington and Jefferson, to Russell Kirk and Milton Friedman. 

<P>
<FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="BLUE"><B>
DEBATE... </B></FONT>
<P>
<DD>
Students hear from top policy experts at <B>intern seminars</B>.  Weekly seminars are conducted by congressional staffers, leading journalists, top Heritage domestic and foreign policy analysts, and Heritage Fellows such as former Attorney General Edwin Meese.
<P>
<FONT FACE="Geneva" COLOR="BLUE"><B>
AND HAVE FUN! </B></FONT>
<P>
<DD>

Heritage's Intern Program sponsors <B>cultural and social activities</B> in Washington, D.C.  Past interns attended a taping of the McLaughlin Group, toured the White House and the Supreme Court, and, of course, played on Heritage's softball team, <I>The Capitalist Tools</I>.  
<P>
